k\n!Opposition<br>Score\n!Opposition<br>Score\n!Opposition<br>Score\n!Rank\n|-\n|align=left|[[Saudi Arabia men's national water polo team|Saudi Arabia men's]]\n|align=left|[[Water polo at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|Men's tournament]]\n|{{wp|INA}}<br>'''D''' 12\u201312\n|{{wp|HKG}}<br>'''W''' 12\u20136\n|{{wp|CHN}}<br>'''L''' 5\u201317\n|{{wp|JPN}}<br>'''L''' 4\u201320\n|3 '''Q'''\n|{{wp|IRI}}<br>'''L''' 7\u201315\n|{{wp|SGP}}<br>'''L''' 5\u20136\n|{{wp|INA}}<br>'''W''' 12\u20138\n|7\n|}\n\n===Men's tournament===\n{{main article|Water polo at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament}}\n\n;Team roster\nHead coach: Bandar Al-Zahrani\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n#Hussain Jaizany (GK)\n#Mohammed Al-Helal (CB)\n#Mohammed Gahal (D)\n#Saeed Taleb (CB)\n#Naif Al-Muntashiri (D)\n#Ayman Al-Aryani (CB)\n#Ahmed Al-Shammary (D)\n#Khaled Al-Harbi (CF) ([[Captain (sports)|C]])\n#Hamed Al-Nefaiei (CF)\n#Bader Al-Dughther (D)\n#Adel Al-Malki (D)\n#Mohammed Al-Khawfi (D)\n#Omar Sharahili (GK)\n{{div col end}}\n\n;Group B\n{{#section:Water polo at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|GB}}\n{{#section:Water polo at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|B1}}\n----\n{{#section:Water polo at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|B4}}\n----\n{{#section:Water polo at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|B8}}\n----\n{{#section:Water polo at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|B9}}\n\n;Quarter-final\n{{#section:Water polo at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|QF2}}\n\n;Classification semifinal (5\u20138)\n{{#section:Water polo at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|R5SF1}}\n\n;Seventh place game\n{{#section:Water polo at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|CR3}}\n\n==Weightlifting==\n{{main article|Weightlifting at the 2018 Asian Games}}\n\n;Men\n{|class=wikitable style=font-size:90%;text-align:center\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Athlete\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Event\n!colspan=\"2\"|Snatch\n!colspan=\"2\"|Clean & Jerk\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Total\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Rank\n|- style=\"font-size:95%\"\n!Result\n!Rank\n!Result\n!Rank\n|-\n|align=left|Mansour Al-Saleem\n|align=left rowspan=2|[[Weightlifting at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's 56 kg|\u221256 kg]]\n|122\n|4\n|142\n|6\n|264\n|6\n|-\n|align=left|Seraj Al-Saleem\n|108\n|8\n|141\n|7\n|249\n|8\n|-\n|align=left|Nawaf Mohammed S Almazaydi\n|align=left|[[Weightlifting at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's 62 kg|\u221262 kg]]\n|<s>115</s>\n|{{Tooltip|DNF|Did not finish}}\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|-\n|align=left|Mahmoud Mohammed Al Humayd\n|align=left rowspan=2|[[Weightlifting at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's 69 kg|\u221269 kg]]\n|142\n|7\n|177\n|8\n|319\n|6\n|-\n|align=left|Mohsen Hussain Al Duhaylib\n|131\n|13\n|166\n|11\n|297\n|12\n|-\n|align=left|Ali Yousef Alothman\n|align=left|[[Weightlifting at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's 85 kg|\u221285 kg]]\n|130\n|9\n|161\n|9\n|291\n|9\n|-\n|align=left|Ali Ahmed Al Khazal\n|align=left|[[Weightlifting at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's 94 kg|\u221294 kg]]\n|150\n|8\n|190\n|5\n|340\n|7\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Nations at the 2018 Asian Games}}\n\n[[Category:Nations at the 2018 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Saudi Arabia at the Asian Games|2018]]\n[[Category:2018 in Saudi Arabian sport|Asian Games]]\n\n{{AsianGames-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jonesey95", "label": "safe", "comment": "FixLintererrors usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saudi_Arabia_at_the_2018_Asian_Games"}
{"title_page": "University of Cincinnati Blue Ash College", "text_new": "{{COI|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = UC Blue Ash College\n| former_name = Raymond Walters College\n| established = 1967\n| type = Public regional campus\n| parent = [[University of Cincinnati]]\n| students = 5,172<ref name=\"headcount\">As of fall 2019. {{cite web | title=15th Day Headcount, Fall Term 2019 | url=https://www.ohiohighered.org/sites/default/files/uploads/data/enrollment/Preliminary_hc_2019_101719.pdf | publisher=Ohio Department of Higher Education | access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n| dean = Robin Lightner\n| city = [[Blue Ash, Ohio|Blue Ash]]\n| state = [[Ohio]]\n| country = United States\n| logo = UC BlueAshInformal vertical CS6.jpg\n| website = [https://ucblueash.edu ucblueash.edu]\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Cincinnati Blue Ash College''' (formerly '''Raymond Walters College''') is a regional campus of the [[University of Cincinnati]] and is located in [[Blue Ash, Ohio]].  It was founded in 1967 as the first regional campus of the university. With an enrollment of about 5,000 students, UC Blue Ash College is one of the largest regional colleges in [[Ohio]].\n\n== History ==\nThe [[University of Cincinnati]] created UC Blue Ash College, known then as Raymond Walters College, as a result of the federal [[Higher Education Act of 1965|Higher Education Act]] that became law in 1965. The legislation helped increase access to higher education for low and middle-income students by strengthening the educational resources for colleges and universities. In Ohio, those resources were invested into existing public universities to create regional colleges that are open access and offer low tuition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/local/blue-ash/2017/09/01/uc-blue-ash-celebrates-years/105198666/|title=UC Blue Ash celebrates 50 years|website=Cincinnati.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n\nUnder the supervision of the inaugural dean, Hilmar Kreuger, the college officially opened its doors on September 25, 1967 with an enrollment of 632 students.\n\n=== Notable milestones ===\n\n* 1969: Dr. Ernest Muntz is named dean of the college and serves until 1990. He is the longest-tenured dean of UC Blue Ash.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*1977: The Department of Math, Physics and Computer Science is one of the first institutions in [[Ohio]] to acquire a super-minicomputer. This technology was unparalleled in local academia at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uccomputinghistory.blogspot.com/|title=University of Cincinnati's Computing History|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n* 1997: The UC Blue Ash Study Abroad Program launches with a course in the [[United Kingdom]]. Since its founding, the program has visited over 15 countries and offered more than 50 courses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/local/blue-ash/2015/06/29/uc-blue-ash-college-students-study-abroad-peru/29459449/|title=UC Blue Ash students visit Peru|website=Cincinnati.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woods|first=Angie L.|last2=Sipple|first2=Susan M.|last3=Otten|first3=Mark R. M.|last4=Roos|first4=Michael E.|date=2017-12-02|title=Navigating Uncharted Waters: Study Abroad Predeparture Activities and the 2-Year-College Student|journal=Community College Journal of Research and Practice|volume=41|issue=12|pages=867\u2013880|doi=10.1080/10668926.2016.1242439|issn=1066-8926}}</ref>\n* 2004: The college launches the Bachelor's in Radiation Science Technology program, its first bachelor's degree program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guidetoonlineschools.com/degrees/radiology|title=2019 Accredited Online Radiology Degrees|website=www.guidetoonlineschools.com|language=English|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.collegecalc.org/majors/medical-radiologic-technology-science---radiation-therapist/|title=Most Affordable Colleges for Medical Radiologic Technology/Science - Radiation Therapist|website=www.collegecalc.org|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n* 2010: The UC Smiles program is created to provide free oral health check-ups to under-served school children in [[Cincinnati metropolitan area|Greater Cincinnati]] at the Dental Hygiene Clinic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvxu.org/post/how-dental-students-are-turning-toothbrushes-treasures|title=How Dental Students Are Turning Toothbrushes Into Treasures|last=Weingartner|first=Tana|website=www.wvxu.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n* 2011: The UC Board of Trustees approve changing the name from Raymond Walters College to UC Blue Ash College.\n* 2011: The college adds its second bachelor's degree, the Bachelor of Technical and Applied Science. \n* 2017: Construction on Progress Hall, a 16,000 square foot building with new classrooms and faculty offices, is completed.\n\n== Campus ==\nThe 135-acre campus, located in [[Blue Ash, Ohio]], consists of six academic buildings. The [[University of Cincinnati]] purchased the land in 1965 from the [[Cincinnati|City of Cincinnati]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blueashhistoricalsociety.org/?page_id=2016|title=Blue Ash History {{!}} Blue Ash Historical Society|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n[[File:Aerial-View-of-Campus.jpg|alt=An aerial view of UC Blue Ash College|thumb|300x300px|UC Blue Ash College]]\n\n== Academics ==\nUC Blue Ash College is accredited by the [[Higher Learning Commission]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hlcommission.org/component/directory/?Itemid=&Action=ShowBasic&instid=1601|title=Higher Learning Commission|website=www.hlcommission.org|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> The college offers more than 50 academic degree and certificate programs, including two bachelor's degrees and the region's only dental hygiene program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bigfuture.collegeboard.org/college-university-search/university-of-cincinnati-blue-ash-college|title=University of Cincinnati: Blue Ash College - The College Board|website=bigfuture.collegeboard.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n{{alumni|date=July 2019}}\n* [[Ronald D. Brown]]: A current member of the [[University of Cincinnati|University of Cincinnati's]] Board of Trustees, Brown has served as CEO of Milacron Inc. and Vice Chairman and COO of The Armor Group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uc.edu/:8443https//uc.edu/trustees/trustees/r_brown|title=Ronald D. Brown|website=University of Cincinnati|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-17}}{{dead link|date=July 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Eric Broyles]]: A UC Blue Ash College alumnus, Broyles graduated with honors from the [[University of Cincinnati]], earned his law degree at the [[University of Virginia School of Law|University of Virginia's School of Law]] and went on to become a corporate attorney, entrepreneur and author. He serves as CEO of ExpertConnect in Washington D.C. and in 2018 donated $1 million to the scholarship fund he previously created at UC Blue Ash College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvxu.org/post/eric-broyles-importance-mentors|title=Eric Broyles On The Importance Of Mentors|last=Monks|first=Michael|website=www.wvxu.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n* [[Andrew Ciarfardini]]: A former member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]] and employee of the [[United States Department of State|U.S. Department of State]], Ciarfardini now serves as Head of Global Corporate Affairs and Chief of Staff to the Executive Chairman and CEO for [[Worldpay, Inc.|Worldpay]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hcrp.blogspot.com/2008/11/state-representative-andrew-ciafardini.html|title=Hamilton County GOP: State Representative Andrew Ciafardini|last=Triantafilou|first=Alex|date=2008-11-14|website=Hamilton County GOP|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n* [[Kara Sanders]]: During her time with the [[United States Department of Labor|U.S. Department of Labor]], Sanders designed and implemented numerous apprenticeship programs. She now works as Craftforce Development Executive at the Messer Construction Company, spearheading local outreach in building trade skills among youth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvxu.org/post/shortage-construction-field-opportunity-young-people|title=Shortage In The Construction Field Is An Opportunity For Young People|last=Monks|first=Michael|website=www.wvxu.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n* [[Bob Schuler|Robert L. Schuler]]: A former member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]] and [[Ohio Senate]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://smartvoter.org/2002/11/05/oh/state/vote/schuler_r/|title=Voter Information for Robert L. Schuler. November 5, 2002 Election|website=smartvoter.org|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://ucblueash.edu/ Official website]\n\n{{University of Cincinnati}}\n{{Colleges and universities in Ohio}}\n{{Public universities in Ohio}}\n\n{{coord|39|14|01|N|84|24|00|W|type:edu_region:US-OH|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Ohio]]\n[[Category:University of Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:Hamilton County, Ohio]]\n[[Category:1967 establishments in Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{COI|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = UC Blue Ash College\n| former_name = Raymond Walters College\n| established = 1967\n| type = Public regional campus\n| parent = [[University of Cincinnati]]\n| dean = Robin Lightner\n| city = [[Blue Ash, Ohio|Blue Ash]]\n| state = [[Ohio]]\n| country = United States\n| logo = UC BlueAshInformal vertical CS6.jpg\n| website = [https://ucblueash.edu ucblueash.edu]\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Cincinnati Blue Ash College''' (formerly '''Raymond Walters College''') is a regional campus of the [[University of Cincinnati]] and is located in [[Blue Ash, Ohio]].  It was founded in 1967 as the first regional campus of the university. With an enrollment of about 5,000 students, UC Blue Ash College is one of the largest regional colleges in [[Ohio]].\n\n== History ==\nThe [[University of Cincinnati]] created UC Blue Ash College, known then as Raymond Walters College, as a result of the federal [[Higher Education Act of 1965|Higher Education Act]] that became law in 1965. The legislation helped increase access to higher education for low and middle-income students by strengthening the educational resources for colleges and universities. In Ohio, those resources were invested into existing public universities to create regional colleges that are open access and offer low tuition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/local/blue-ash/2017/09/01/uc-blue-ash-celebrates-years/105198666/|title=UC Blue Ash celebrates 50 years|website=Cincinnati.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n\nUnder the supervision of the inaugural dean, Hilmar Kreuger, the college officially opened its doors on September 25, 1967 with an enrollment of 632 students.\n\n=== Notable milestones ===\n\n* 1969: Dr. Ernest Muntz is named dean of the college and serves until 1990. He is the longest-tenured dean of UC Blue Ash.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*1977: The Department of Math, Physics and Computer Science is one of the first institutions in [[Ohio]] to acquire a super-minicomputer. This technology was unparalleled in local academia at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uccomputinghistory.blogspot.com/|title=University of Cincinnati's Computing History|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n* 1997: The UC Blue Ash Study Abroad Program launches with a course in the [[United Kingdom]]. Since its founding, the program has visited over 15 countries and offered more than 50 courses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/local/blue-ash/2015/06/29/uc-blue-ash-college-students-study-abroad-peru/29459449/|title=UC Blue Ash students visit Peru|website=Cincinnati.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woods|first=Angie L.|last2=Sipple|first2=Susan M.|last3=Otten|first3=Mark R. M.|last4=Roos|first4=Michael E.|date=2017-12-02|title=Navigating Uncharted Waters: Study Abroad Predeparture Activities and the 2-Year-College Student|journal=Community College Journal of Research and Practice|volume=41|issue=12|pages=867\u2013880|doi=10.1080/10668926.2016.1242439|issn=1066-8926}}</ref>\n* 2004: The college launches the Bachelor's in Radiation Science Technology program, its first bachelor's degree program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guidetoonlineschools.com/degrees/radiology|title=2019 Accredited Online Radiology Degrees|website=www.guidetoonlineschools.com|language=English|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.collegecalc.org/majors/medical-radiologic-technology-science---radiation-therapist/|title=Most Affordable Colleges for Medical Radiologic Technology/Science - Radiation Therapist|website=www.collegecalc.org|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n* 2010: The UC Smiles program is created to provide free oral health check-ups to under-served school children in [[Cincinnati metropolitan area|Greater Cincinnati]] at the Dental Hygiene Clinic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvxu.org/post/how-dental-students-are-turning-toothbrushes-treasures|title=How Dental Students Are Turning Toothbrushes Into Treasures|last=Weingartner|first=Tana|website=www.wvxu.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n* 2011: The UC Board of Trustees approve changing the name from Raymond Walters College to UC Blue Ash College.\n* 2011: The college adds its second bachelor's degree, the Bachelor of Technical and Applied Science. \n* 2017: Construction on Progress Hall, a 16,000 square foot building with new classrooms and faculty offices, is completed.\n\n== Campus ==\nThe 135-acre campus, located in [[Blue Ash, Ohio]], consists of six academic buildings. The [[University of Cincinnati]] purchased the land in 1965 from the [[Cincinnati|City of Cincinnati]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blueashhistoricalsociety.org/?page_id=2016|title=Blue Ash History {{!}} Blue Ash Historical Society|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n[[File:Aerial-View-of-Campus.jpg|alt=An aerial view of UC Blue Ash College|thumb|300x300px|UC Blue Ash College]]\n\n== Academics ==\nUC Blue Ash College is accredited by the [[Higher Learning Commission]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hlcommission.org/component/directory/?Itemid=&Action=ShowBasic&instid=1601|title=Higher Learning Commission|website=www.hlcommission.org|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> The college offers more than 50 academic degree and certificate programs, including two bachelor's degrees and the region's only dental hygiene program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bigfuture.collegeboard.org/college-university-search/university-of-cincinnati-blue-ash-college|title=University of Cincinnati: Blue Ash College - The College Board|website=bigfuture.collegeboard.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n{{alumni|date=July 2019}}\n* [[Ronald D. Brown]]: A current member of the [[University of Cincinnati|University of Cincinnati's]] Board of Trustees, Brown has served as CEO of Milacron Inc. and Vice Chairman and COO of The Armor Group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uc.edu/:8443https//uc.edu/trustees/trustees/r_brown|title=Ronald D. Brown|website=University of Cincinnati|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-17}}{{dead link|date=July 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Eric Broyles]]: A UC Blue Ash College alumnus, Broyles graduated with honors from the [[University of Cincinnati]], earned his law degree at the [[University of Virginia School of Law|University of Virginia's School of Law]] and went on to become a corporate attorney, entrepreneur and author. He serves as CEO of ExpertConnect in Washington D.C. and in 2018 donated $1 million to the scholarship fund he previously created at UC Blue Ash College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvxu.org/post/eric-broyles-importance-mentors|title=Eric Broyles On The Importance Of Mentors|last=Monks|first=Michael|website=www.wvxu.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n* [[Andrew Ciarfardini]]: A former member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]] and employee of the [[United States Department of State|U.S. Department of State]], Ciarfardini now serves as Head of Global Corporate Affairs and Chief of Staff to the Executive Chairman and CEO for [[Worldpay, Inc.|Worldpay]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hcrp.blogspot.com/2008/11/state-representative-andrew-ciafardini.html|title=Hamilton County GOP: State Representative Andrew Ciafardini|last=Triantafilou|first=Alex|date=2008-11-14|website=Hamilton County GOP|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n* [[Kara Sanders]]: During her time with the [[United States Department of Labor|U.S. Department of Labor]], Sanders designed and implemented numerous apprenticeship programs. She now works as Craftforce Development Executive at the Messer Construction Company, spearheading local outreach in building trade skills among youth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvxu.org/post/shortage-construction-field-opportunity-young-people|title=Shortage In The Construction Field Is An Opportunity For Young People|last=Monks|first=Michael|website=www.wvxu.org|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n* [[Bob Schuler|Robert L. Schuler]]: A former member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]] and [[Ohio Senate]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://smartvoter.org/2002/11/05/oh/state/vote/schuler_r/|title=Voter Information for Robert L. Schuler. November 5, 2002 Election|website=smartvoter.org|access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://ucblueash.edu/ Official website]\n\n{{University of Cincinnati}}\n{{Colleges and universities in Ohio}}\n{{Public universities in Ohio}}\n\n{{coord|39|14|01|N|84|24|00|W|type:edu_region:US-OH|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Ohio]]\n[[Category:University of Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:Hamilton County, Ohio]]\